title: Marcus Aurelius Felix
description: A citizen working as centurion in a provincial legionary base, Marcus keeps careful accounts of deductions from pay for infractions among his soldiers and worries about setting his non-citizen children up for success (his wife isn’t a citizen, so his children aren’t).
occupation: centurion in a provincial legionary base
family_status: unofficially married to a local woman; two young children

title: Livia Helpis
description: A freed hairdresser in the capital city Rome, Livia maintains long-term relationships with elite female clients who helped her secure her manumission.
family_status: Unmarried; supports her elderly former owner

title: Tiberius Claudius Dionysius
description: He carries a wax tablet everywhere; his whole social identity is tied to keeping the numbers straight.
occupation: account clerk (tabularius) for a shipping company
family_status: married to a freedwoman; two adult children (freeborn citizens)

title: 1883 reconstruction of Eratosthenes' map
description: Map of the world according to Eratostenes as reconstructed by E.H. Bunbury in 'A history of ancient geography among the Greeks and Romans, from the earliest ages till the fall of the Roman Empire' (1883).
source: E.H. Bunbury, A history of ancient geography among the Greeks and Romans, from the earliest ages till the fall of the Roman Empire (1883), Internet Archive, https://archive.org/details/historyofancient00bunb/page/666/mode/2up
